a:5:{s:5:"title";s:73:"Lime CRM introduces Portal Communication for portal messaging on Tickets";s:16:"text-format-info";a:3:{s:10:"text-final";s:1524:"<p>Lime CRM rolled out Portal Communication, bringing portal-based customer messages into the agent workspace as a dedicated, ticket-linked conversation view.</p>
<h2>What’s new</h2>
<p>Portal messages are displayed as threaded conversations directly on the Ticket.</p>
<p>Each message is labeled with incoming/outgoing direction.</p>
<p>Agents can open the conversation on the Ticket and reply from the web client using built-in editor/actions.</p>
<h3>What stays in the portal</h3>
<p>Portal Communication does not replace portal functionality. The portal still handles:</p>
<ul>
<li>authentication</li>
<li>notifications</li>
<li>message synchronization</li>
</ul>
<p>Portal Communication adds the CRM-side interface where agents work with the thread.</p>
<h3>Compatibility and rollout</h3>
<p>Included by default in new Lime Portal implementations.</p>
<p>Recommended for new third-party portal integrations.</p>
<p>For existing portal setups, it is not enabled by default, but can be added and configured through Lime.</p>
<h3>Multiple portals supported</h3>
<p>Portal Communication can be used with more than one portal (e. g., a tenant portal and a supplier/contractor portal). Both can link back to the same Ticket in Lime CRM while keeping conversations separated when needed.</p>
<p>Learn more: <a href="https://lime-limepkg-portal.readthedocs-hosted.com/en/latest/#what-this-add-on-does">https://lime-limepkg-portal.readthedocs-hosted.com/en/latest/#what-this-add-on-does</a></p>
